THE STATE OF SOUTH CAROLINA
In The Court of Appeals

  
    
      
Jane &amp; John Doe, Respondents,
v.
Richard Roe; Mary M.; John Roe (Whose true identity is unknown); and Baby Boy Jay, A Minor Under the Age Seven (7) Years, Defendants,
Of Whom Richard Roe is the Appellant.
      
    
  


Appeal From Spartanburg County
Â James F. Fraley, Jr., Family Court Judge

Opinion No.Â  4119
Heard May 9, 2006 â€“ Filed June 5, 2006

AFFIRMED


  
    
      
William G. Rhoden, of Gaffney, for Appellant.
James Fletcher Thompson, of Spartanburg, for Respondents.
Susan A. Fretwell, of Spartanburg, Guardian Ad
Litem.
      
    
  


ANDERSON, J.:Â  Richard Roe, the biological father of Baby Boy Jay, appeals (1) the family courtâ€™s ruling that Roeâ€™s consent for adoption was not required under section 20-7-1690 of the South Carolina Code, and (2) the courtâ€™s termination of Roeâ€™s parental rights.Â  We affirm.
FACTUAL/PROCEDURAL BACKGROUND
 Melanie gave birth to Jay on January 19, 2005, and executed a consent for adoption form on January 20, 2005.Â  Jane and John Doe initiated this action by filing for adoption of Jay on January 24, 2005.Â  The Does have had custody of Jay since January 21, 2005.Â  
 Roe timely filed an answer and counter-claim seeking custody of Jay.Â  DNA testing confirmed that Roe is Jayâ€™s biological father.Â  The case was tried on May 9 and 11, 2005 and resulted in a ruling that Roeâ€™s consent was not required under South Carolina Code Annotated section 20-7-1690.Â  In addition, the court terminated his parental rights.Â  
 Roe, who has been married to Martha Roe since April of 2000, separated from his wife in March of 2004 and moved in with Melanie.Â  Within a few weeks, Roe returned to live with his wife. Shortly thereafter, Melanie discovered she was pregnant and informed Roe.Â  On June 16, 2004, Melanie entered a drug rehabilitation center where she stayed until September 2, 2004.Â  While she was in rehabilitation, Roe visited her and called her on the phone.Â  The parties disagreed on the number of visitsâ€”Melanie estimated six visits, Roe recalled twelve or thirteen.Â  By early August, the calls and visits suddenly stopped.Â  Melanie averred:

  
    
      
        A.&nbsp;&nbsp;
         In the beginning, he called a lot, but he just quit calling and quit coming, and I didnâ€™t know what happened to him.
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        Q.
         Before you got out, recognizing you got out September 2nd, â€™04, how much before the time that you got outâ€”how many days or weeks or months did he stop coming to visit or stop calling?
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        A.
         About a month.
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        Q.&nbsp;
         Had yâ€™all had this falling out or something?
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        A.&nbsp;
         No.Â  He showed up with a card and a pack of cigarettes.Â  And, the lady there told meâ€”he didnâ€™t even see me, it was Wednesday; it was not visit day; Thursday was visit day.Â  And, when I came backâ€”I think I was in class or something, but when I came back to where we lived, she gave me the card and the cigarettes.
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        Q.
         That was it?
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        A.&nbsp;
         I never heard from him again until December.
      
    
  

 During the time that Roe did visit, he gave Melanie some money, brought her cigarettes, and took her out for food on several occasions. Â 

  
    
      
        Q.
         . . . Was there anything that Roe ever brought you that helped you while you were in there. . . ?
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        A.&nbsp;
         He got me some food.
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        Q.&nbsp;
         Yâ€™all went out to eat?Â  You could check out a couple of times?
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        A.&nbsp;&nbsp;
         On Thursday, he could go eat with me, if I remember.
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        Q.&nbsp;
         And, I think you estimated on how many occasions during the time he came?
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        A.&nbsp;
         We went to Subway twice and, on a Sunday, he brought me KFC once.
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        Q.&nbsp;
         Subway twice; KFC onceâ€”twice; is that right?
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        A.
         Yes.
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        Q.
         And, Twenty Bucks?
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        A.&nbsp;
         Yes.
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        Q.&nbsp;
         Could it have been Thirty Bucks?
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        A.&nbsp;&nbsp;
         It could have been Thirty Bucks.
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        Q.&nbsp;
         Could it have been Fifty Bucks?
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        A.&nbsp;
         No, it wasnâ€™t.
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        Q.&nbsp;
         That was just one time, and it was in cash.
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        A.&nbsp;&nbsp;
         Yesâ€”well, no, he mainly gave me Ten and Twenty on different occasions, but it was not more than Fifty Dollars altogether.
      
    
  

Roe confessed, â€œI gave her very little money while she was in there,â€ but estimated he gave her between fifty and one hundred dollars.Â  He averred he brought her cigarettes and soda â€œjust about every week.â€Â Â Â  
Melanie left the rehabilitation center on September 2.Â  After staying one night with a friend, and several nights with her brother, she returned to her motherâ€™s home in Gaffney, South Carolina.Â  On September 7, Melanie obtained phone service in her name at her motherâ€™s residence.Â  Melanie tried unsuccessfully to reach Roe by phone on several occasions, calling Roeâ€™s mother and wife to no avail.Â  For approximately two weeks in October, Melanie moved out from her motherâ€™s house and stayed with her brother Adam and his girlfriend Carla.Â  She returned to her motherâ€™s in Gaffney and stayed there until December 3, 2004, when she moved back in with Adam and Carla.Â  
Although Melanie avoided DSS, she declared she never attempted to evade Roe.

  
    
      
        Q.&nbsp;
         Have you ever failed to answer the door for Roe?
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        A.&nbsp;
         Roe never knocked on the door.Â  We knew who was at the door all the time.
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        Q.&nbsp;
         Did you ever hide from Roe?
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        A.&nbsp;
         No, I did not.
      
    
  

Melanieâ€™s brother, Adam, and Adamâ€™s girlfriend, Carla, confirmed that Melanie never hid from Roe, but rather attempted to contact him.Â  Adam testified as follows at trial:

  
    
      
        Q.
         At any time when you were staying with your mom and with Melanie at Kendrick Street, were you aware of any steps that were made to try to hide Melanie from Roe?
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        A.&nbsp;
         No, sir.
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        Q.
         Are you aware of any steps that were taken from Melanie to find Roe?
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        A.&nbsp;
         A few.
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        Q.&nbsp;
         What were you aware of that was done?
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        A.&nbsp;&nbsp;
         I was aware of her few phone calls that were made.
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        Q.
         Did you ever make any phone calls?
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        A.&nbsp;&nbsp;
         One or two.
      
    
  

Carla provided a similar account:

  
    
      
        Q.&nbsp;&nbsp;
         Were you aware of any veil of secrecy or any kind of concerted effort that was made to hide the pregnancy from Roe?
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        A.&nbsp;
        No.
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        Q.&nbsp;
         Are you aware of any steps that were taken actually to locate Roe during this period of time?
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        A.&nbsp;
         Yes.
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
         Q.&nbsp;&nbsp;
         What were you aware of?
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        A.&nbsp;
         Melanie had used the phone a couple of times trying to call.Â  She couldnâ€™t get through.Â  Adam had called a couple of times and couldnâ€™t get through.Â  They just couldnâ€™t find him.Â 
      
    
  

However, the evidence does suggest that Roe hid from Melanie.Â  Adam recounted a time in December when he had a chance encounter with Roe.

  
    
      
        Q.&nbsp;&nbsp;
         What happened that day?
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        A.
         Roe drove up the street.Â  I was outside.Â  He stopped to talk to me.
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        Q.
         What did Roe say?
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        A.&nbsp;
         He asked me if I knew where my sister was.
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        Q.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
         What did you say to him?
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        A.
         I asked him where he wasâ€”where he had been, Iâ€™m sorry.
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        Q.
         What was his response to that?
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        A.&nbsp;
         He said he was trying to hide out.
      
    
  

Carla described an occasion when Roe stopped at the service station where Adam and Carla worked.Â  She averred: â€œ. . . I had asked at one point â€˜[W]hat happened to you, Roe; you just disappeared?â€™Â  And, he kind of looked down and said: â€˜That was my plan.â€™â€Â  
From December 3 until Jay was born Melanie stayed with her brother.Â  Roe spoke with Melanieâ€™s brother and left a card and a pillow for her sometime in December.Â  The card read, â€œ21 More Day[s],â€ a statement apparently intended to mislead Melanie into believing Roe was soon to be divorced from his wife.Â  
On January 3, 2005, Roe stopped by Adamâ€™s trailer to install a car battery.Â  Melanie was there, and Roe stayed for approximately fifteen minutes.Â  According to Roe, â€œshe showed me a picture of the ultrasound and I told her I didnâ€™t really have time; I just wanted to make sure she was O. K.â€Â  Melanie testified:

  
    
      
        Q.
         At that time, did he stay a long time?Â  Did he talk to you about the baby and your plans together?Â  Did yâ€™all sit down and â€“what happened?
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        A.&nbsp;&nbsp;
         I was sitting on the couch; I showed him the ultrasound; he helped me with the battery in the car.
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        Q.
         Did he leave you any money?
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        A.
         No.
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        Q.
         Did he come back after that January 3rd visit again before the baby was born?
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        A.&nbsp;&nbsp;
         No, he did not.
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        Q.&nbsp;
         Had you left the Evans Trailer Park?
      
      
        
        &nbsp;
      
      
        A.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
         No, he told me that he would be back, and he never came back.
      
    
  

Melanie did not see Roe again until after she gave birth.Â  On February 12, 2005, after learning of the suit for adoption by the Does, Roe purchased several items including blankets, pacifiers, and a diaper bag from Target.Â  
The family court ruled that Roe was aware that Melanie was pregnant, knew of her location, and was informed that she was considering the option of adoption.Â  According to the court, Roe â€œabdicated his responsibility to Melanie and to the unborn child.â€Â  Therefore, the court found his consent to the adoption was not required and terminated his parental rights.Â  
STANDARD OF REVIEW
In appeals from the family court, this Court may find facts in accordance with its own view of the preponderance of the evidence.Â  Dearybury v. Dearybury, 351 S.C. 278, 569 S.E.2d 367 (2002); Lanier v. Lanier, 364 S.C. 211, 612 S.E.2d 456 (Ct. App. 2005); Nasser-Moghaddassi v. Moghaddassi, 364 S.C. 182, 612 S.E.2d 707 (Ct. App. 2005); Emery v. Smith, 361 S.C. 207, 603 S.E.2d 598 (Ct. App. 2004) (citing Rutherford v. Rutherford, 307 S.C. 199, 414 S.E.2d 157 (1992)).Â Â  However, this broad scope of review does not require us to disregard the family courtâ€™s findings.Â  Holler v. Holler, 364 S.C. 256, 261, 612 S.E.2d 469, 472 (Ct. App. 2005).Â  Bowers v. Bowers, 349 S.C. 85, 561 S.E.2d 610 (Ct. App. 2002); Badeaux v. Davis, 337 S.C. 195, 522 S.E.2d 835 (Ct. App. 1999).Â  Nor must we ignore the fact that the trial judge, who saw and heard the witnesses, was in a better position to evaluate their credibility and assign comparative weight to their testimony.Â  Lacke v. Lacke, 362 S.C. 302, 608 S.E.2d 147 (Ct. App. 2005); Murdock v. Murdock, 338 S.C. 322, 526 S.E.2d 241 (Ct. App. 1999); see also Dorchester County Depâ€™t of Soc. Servs. v. Miller, 324 S.C. 445, 477 S.E.2d 476 (Ct. App. 1996) (noting that because the appellate court lacks the opportunity for direct observation of witnesses, it should accord great deference to the family courtâ€™s findings where matters of credibility are involved).
LAW/ANALYSIS
I.Â  An Unwed Fatherâ€™s Consent for Adoption
A.Â  Section 20-7-1690
South Carolina Code Ann. section 20-7-1690 (Supp. 2005), provides, in pertinent part: 

(A) Consent or relinquishment for the purpose of adoption is required of the following persons:
Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  . . . .
(5) the father of a child born when the father was not married to the childâ€™s mother, if the child was placed with the prospective adoptive parents six months or less after the childâ€™s birth, but only if:
  
(a) the father openly lived with the child or the childâ€™s mother for a continuous period of six months immediately preceding the placement of the child for adoption, and the father openly held himself out to be the father of the child during the six months period; or
(b) the father paid a fair and reasonable sum, based on the fatherâ€™s financial ability, for the support of the child or for expenses incurred in connection with the motherâ€™s pregnancy or with the birth of the child, including, but not limited to, medical, hospital, and nursing expenses.
  

S.C. Code Ann. Â§ 20-7-1690 (Supp. 2005) (emphasis added).Â  Roe did not provide a reasonable sum for the support of the child or for expenses incurred in connection with Melanieâ€™s pregnancy as outlined in the statute.Â  However, under certain limited circumstances, our courts will excuse an unwed father for failure to meet the requirements of the statute.Â Â  
B.Â  Abernathy and Its Progeny
The seminal case of Abernathy v. Baby Boy, 313 S.C. 27, 437 S.E.2d 25 (1993), held that even though an unwed father fails to meet the literal requirements of section 20-7-1690, he may nonetheless be afforded constitutional protection when he undertakes sufficient prompt and good faith efforts to assume parental responsibility and to comply with the statute.Â  The biological mother and father in Abernathy began a â€œcasual sexual relationshipâ€ while both were on active duty in the Navy.Â  313 S.C. at 29, 437 S.E.2d at 27.Â  Soon after Julie and Mitchell discovered Julie was pregnant, Mitchell was forced to leave for sea duty.Â  He gave Julie use of his car and access to his bank account, and offered to send her to college while he stayed home to care for the child.Â  Julie, however, decided she did not want to be involved with Mitchell.Â  She put the car in storage and used the bank account only to store the car and to pay a speeding ticket fine for Mitchell.Â  Upon Mitchellâ€™s return from sea Julie â€œrebuffed his advances and rejected his offer of marriage. . . . Julie thereafter avoided contact with Mitchell, refused his telephone calls, and â€˜was kind of hiding away from him.â€™â€Â  Id.Â Â  Mitchell received notice that Julie had given birth and that the Abernathys had commenced an action to adopt the child.Â  Mitchell contested the adoption.Â  The trial court determined he possessed the right to refuse consent to the adoption.Â  Our supreme court affirmed.

First, the appellants maintained â€œan unwed fatherâ€™s consent to adoption is not required unless he complies with the literal requirements of section 20- 7-1690(A)(5)(b), which mandates that a father provide for the support of his child before the State is compelled to seek his consent to the adoption of the child.â€Â  313 S.C. at 31, 437 S.E.2d at 28.Â  The court did not agree:

 The United States Supreme Court has recognized that an unwed father may possess a relationship with his child that is entitled to constitutional protection.Â  Stanley v. Illinois, 405 U.S. 645, 92 S.Ct. 1208, 31 L.Ed.2d 551 (1972).Â  However, â€œparental rights do not spring full-blown from the biological connection between parent and child. They require relationships more enduring.â€Â  Lehr v. Robertson, 463 U.S. 248, 260, 103 S.Ct. 2985, 2992, 77 L.Ed.2d 614, 626 (1983) (quoting Caban v. Mohammed, 441 U.S. 380, 99 S.Ct. 1760, 60 L.Ed.2d 297 (1979)).Â  Thus, an unwed father must demonstrate a full commitment to the responsibilities of parenthood by coming forward to participate in the rearing of his child before his interest in personal contact with his child acquires substantial constitutional protection.Â  Id., 463 U.S. at 261, 103 S.Ct. at 2993, 77 L.Ed.2d at 626.Â  The mere existence of a biological link does not merit equivalent constitutional protection.Â  Id.
 When a child is first born, an unwed father possesses an â€œopportunity no other male possesses to develop a relationship with his offspring.â€Â  Id. at 262, 103 S.Ct. at 2993, 77 L.Ed.2d at 627.Â  However, this opportunity interest is constitutionally protected only to the extent that the biological father who claims protection wants to make the commitments and perform the responsibilities that give rise to a developed relationship, because it is only the combination of biology and custodial responsibility that the Constitution ultimately protects.Â  E. Buchanan, The Constitutional Rights of Unwed Fathers Before and After Lehr v. Robertson, 45 Ohio State L.J. 313, 368 (1984) (hereinafter Unwed Fathers).Â  The specific acts undertaken by the unwed father to preserve his inchoate relationship with his child, as well as the nature of the relationship he wishes to foster with the child, are of considerable importance in determining whether the unwed father has evinced a commitment to his child deserving of protection. See id. at 352; cf. Lehr, 463 U.S. at 262, 103 S.Ct. at 2994, 77 L.Ed.2d at 627 (appellant never had any significant custodial, personal, or financial relationship with child, and did not seek to establish a legal tie until after the child was two years old).Â  Moreover, the opportunity interest is of limited duration as a constitutionally significant interest because of the childâ€™s need for early permanence and stability in parental relationships.Â  Unwed Fathers at 365.
 Against this background, we must ascertain the interaction between the requirements of section 20-7-1690(A)(5)(b) and the unusual facts before us.Â  As always, our primary function in interpreting a statute is to ascertain the intent of the Legislature. Spartanburg Cty. Depâ€™t of Social Svcs. v. Little, 309 S.C. 122, 420 S.E.2d 499 (1992). A statute must receive a practical, reasonable, and fair interpretation consonant with the purpose, design, and policy of the lawmakers.Â  Id.Â  We find that by enacting section 20-7-1690(A)(5)(b), the Legislature contemplated establishing general minimum standards by which an unwed father timely may demonstrate his commitment to the child, and his desire to â€œgrasp [the] opportunity,â€ Lehr, 463 U.S. at 262, 103 S.Ct. at 2993, 77 L.Ed.2d at 627, to assume full responsibility for his child.Â  However, as shown by the events leading to this appeal, an unwed fatherâ€™s ability to cultivate his opportunity interest in his child can be thwarted by the refusal of the mother to accept the fatherâ€™s expressions of interest in and commitment to the child.Â  Accordingly, we conclude that an unwed father is entitled to constitutional protection not only when he meets the literal requirements of section 20-7- 1690(A)(5)(b), but also when he undertakes sufficient prompt and good faith efforts to assume parental responsibility and to comply with the statute.Â  See In re Chandini, 166 A.D.2d 599, 560 N.Y.S.2d 886 (1990); In re Adoption of Baby Girl S., 141 Misc.2d 905, 535 N.Y.S.2d 676 (N.Y.Surr.1988); In re Baby Girl Eason, 257 Ga. 292, 358 S.E.2d 459 (1987); In re Riggs, 612 S.W.2d 461 (Tenn.Ct.App.1980), cert. denied, 450 U.S. 921, 101 S.Ct. 1370, 67 L.Ed.2d 349 (1981).Â  To mandate strict compliance with section 20-7-1690(A)(5)(b) would make an unwed fatherâ€™s right to withhold his consent to adoption dependent upon the whim of the unwed mother.Â  See In re Adoption of Baby Girl S., 141 Misc.2d 905, 535 N.Y.S.2d 676 (N.Y.Surr.1988).

313 S.C. at 31-33, 437 S.E.2d at 28-29.
The court concluded Mitchellâ€™s efforts were sufficient to require his consent to the adoption.

Â It is undisputed that Mitchell attempted to provide monetary support to Julie during her pregnancy, but his offers were rejected by her.Â  In addition, Mitchell endeavored to keep apprised of Julieâ€™s progress during the pregnancy, but she shielded herself from contact with him, even to the point of complaining to her superiors that Mitchell was harassing her by his numerous telephone calls.Â  Mitchell appeared at the hospital after learning that the child had been born and offered to pay medical expenses related to the birth, but was told there were no expenses because he and Julie were in the Navy.Â  Although Mitchell sought no legal advice regarding the means available for him to protect his parental interest in the child, his lack of action was engendered by Julieâ€™s assurance to him that she would not place the child for adoption.Â  Further, Mitchell immediately manifested his willingness to assume sole custody of the child once he discovered that adoption proceedings had commenced.
 Time and circumstances may limit the protectibility of an unwed fatherâ€™s interest in his child.Â  The values that underlie protection require that the father take advantage of his opportunity to develop a relationship with his child early and completely.Â  Unwed Fathers at 364-67, 381-82.Â  Here, Mitchell timely demonstrated a willingness to develop a full custodial relationship with his child.Â  Accordingly, we find that the trial judge did not err in ruling that Mitchellâ€™s consent to the adoption was required, and that the adoption failed as the result of Mitchellâ€™s withholding of his consent.

313 S.C. at 33, 437 S.E.2d at 29.
In Ex parte Black, 330 S.C. 431, 499 S.E.2d 229 (Ct. App. 1998), Contius Black and Martha Jane Dubose were both high school students when they began a sexual relationship.Â  Black transferred to a nearby school and the two eventually ended their relationship.Â  Dubose discovered she was pregnant and attempted to contact Black.Â  She called his parentsâ€™ house and was told that he no longer lived there, although this information was apparently false.Â  Dubose gave birth on June 20, 1995, and gave the child over for adoption two days later.Â  
Black learned that Dubose might be pregnant in October or November of 1995.Â  In December 1995 he had a â€œchance meetingâ€ with Dubose and learned she had delivered the child, given her up for adoption, and that he was the biological father.Â  Black and his new wife contacted the adoption agency and Black was eventually added as a party to the adoption action.Â  The family court determined â€œBlackâ€™s consent for the adoption of the child was not necessary because of his â€˜failure to timely demonstrate a willingness to develop a custodial relationship with this child.â€™â€Â  330 S.C. at 433-34, 499 S.E.2d at 231.Â  We affirmed:

We find no merit to Blackâ€™s argument that the family court erred in finding he failed to timely demonstrate a willingness to develop a full custodial relationship with his daughter.
 If the biological father of a child was not married to the childâ€™s mother at the time the child was born and the child was placed with prospective adoptive parents six months or less after the childâ€™s birth, the fatherâ€™s consent or relinquishment for the purpose of adoption is necessary if the father paid a fair and reasonable sum, based on his financial ability, toward either the childâ€™s support or expenses incurred in connection with the motherâ€™s pregnancy or with the birth of the child.Â  S.C. Code Ann. Â§ 20-7-1690(A)(5)(b) (Supp. 1997).Â Â  An unwed father, however, is entitled to a relationship with his child not only when he meets the literal requirements of this section, â€œbut also when he undertakes sufficient prompt and good-faith efforts to assume parental responsibility and to comply with the statute.â€Â  Abernathy v. Baby Boy, 313 S.C. 27, 32, 437 S.E.2d 25, 29 (1993) (emphasis added).

 Because section 20-7-1690(A)(5)(b) explicitly conditions the necessity of a fatherâ€™s acquiescence in an adoption on his payment of support or financial assistance to the birth mother, any steps Black may have taken to assert his parental rights are insufficient to protect his relationship with his child unless accompanied by a prompt, good-faith effort to assume responsibility for either a financial contribution to the childâ€™s welfare or assistance in paying for the birth motherâ€™s pregnancy or childbirth expenses.Â  Here, the record contains no evidence that Black attempted at any time to help Dubose or Bethany Christian Services with pregnancy or childbirth expenses.Â  Moreover, even assuming Black is correct that he took prompt measures to determine paternity and assert his parental rights after Dubose told him about the child, he admitted he never offered to support the child, even after receiving the results of the paternity test, which were available about five months before the final hearing.Â  Although the family court relied primarily on Blackâ€™s lack of diligence in making inquiries about Duboseâ€™s pregnancy, the record evidence of his failure to offer support for the child as of the date of the final hearing warrants our affirmance of the family court order.Â  See Rule 220(c), SCACR (â€œThe appellate court may affirm any ruling, order, or judgment upon any ground(s) appearing in the Record on Appeal.â€).

Black, 330 S.C. at 434-35, 499 S.E.2d at 231-32 (footnote omitted).
Teenagers Christine Lovin and Samuel Dunlap were involved in a sexual relationship in Parag v. Baby Boy Lovin, 333 S.C. 221, 508 S.E.2d 590 (Ct. App. 1998).Â  Dunlap bought her a pregnancy test when she informed him she might be pregnant, but Lovin did not give him the results.Â  The two terminated their relationship in December 1994 or January 1995.Â  Dunlap continued to inquire whether Lovin was pregnant, but Lovin would neither admit nor deny the pregnancy.Â  She gave birth on July 8, 1995, and gave the baby up for adoption.Â  Lovin did not tell Dunlap about the birth until October 1995.Â  The Parags, in connection with their action to adopt Baby Boy Lovin, hired investigator Oehler to locate the childâ€™s father.Â  Oehler contacted Dunlap in January of 1996.Â  Initially, Dunlap indicated â€œhe was planning to attend college on a football scholarship and the birth of the child interfered with his life.Â  He stated he was not interested in having the child, but was interested in releasing the child for adoption[.]â€Â  333 S.C. at 224, 508 S.E.2d at 592.Â  A few days later, he changed his mind; â€œafter talking with his grandmother and father, he thought he wanted to have the child for them to rear.â€Â  Id.Â  
The Parags commenced an action seeking adoption and the termination of Dunlapâ€™s parental rights.Â  The family court concluded Dunlap had shown sufficient good faith efforts to assume parental responsibility and was entitled to protection under section 20-7-1690 and Abernathy.Â  Adoption was accordingly denied.Â  We disagreed and reversed, noting both the pre- and post-birth shortfalls of Dunlap.

It is incumbent . . . upon the unwed father to demonstrate a full commitment to the responsibilities of parenthood by coming forward to participate in the rearing of the child before he may acquire substantial constitutional protection, and the mere existence of a biological link does not merit equivalent constitutional protection.Â  While the unwed father possesses an opportunity to develop a relationship with his offspring, this opportunity is of limited duration as a constitutionally significant interest because of the childâ€™s need for early permanence and stability in parental relationships.Â  As stated by the court in Abernathy, â€œTime and circumstances may limit the protectibility of an unwed fatherâ€™s interest in his child.Â  The values that underlie protection require that the father take advantage of his opportunity to develop a relationship with his child early and completely.â€Â  313 S.C. at 33, 437 S.E.2d at 29 (emphasis added). Thus, the unwed father must timely â€œdemonstrate his commitment to the child, and his desire to grasp the opportunity.â€Â  313 S.C. at 32, 437 S.E.2d at 29.
Turning to the facts at hand, we find Dunlap has failed to demonstrate sufficient prompt and good faith efforts to assume parental responsibility and comply with the statute.Â  Dunlap was aware that Lovin might be pregnant in November of 1994.Â  While Dunlap claims he was thwarted in his efforts to assist Lovin with the pregnancy by her avoidance of him, the record clearly shows that in October 1995, Lovin informed Dunlap of the pregnancy and the birth of his child.Â  He was further aware at that time that the child was placed for adoption and he correctly assumed the child was in the area where Lovin had given birth.Â  From October of 1995, Dunlap had information with which he could have sought the exact location of his child and made efforts to cultivate a relationship with the child and assume parental responsibility.Â  However, he failed to take any action until he was contacted by the adoption investigator, three months later.Â  Even then, the record evinces the extent of his efforts to be only submission to paternity testing and participation in the adoption action.Â  There is absolutely no evidence that Dunlap was thwarted in any way from demonstrating his commitment to the child once he learned of the childâ€™s birth.Â  It is uncontested Dunlap never offered any financial support or assistance to Lovin in connection with the expenses of the pregnancy and birth after learning of the childâ€™s birth.Â  Further, the record shows Dunlap never offered any financial support for the child after learning of the childâ€™s birth. See Ex parte Black, 330 S.C. 431, 499 S.E.2d 229 (Ct. App. 1998) (assuming unwed father took prompt measures to determine paternity and assert parental rights after biological mother informed father of childâ€™s existence, where father failed to offer to support child or assist in medical expenses, his consent to adoption was not required under Â§ 20-7-1690(A)(5)(b)).Â  We therefore conclude Dunlap has failed to timely demonstrate his commitm