Brown, 331 S.C. at 497-98, 489 S.E.2d at 921. 
The supreme court, in Doe v. Queen, 347 S.C. 4, 552 S.E.2d 761 (2001), held that the unwed fatherâ€™s efforts to assume parental responsibility were sufficient to require his consent to adoption.Â  The biological mother informed Queen that she was pregnant and wanted an abortion.Â  Queen attempted to convince the mother to keep the child.Â  The two ended their relationship, and the mother informed Queen she had aborted the child.Â  The mother and her new boyfriend signed a criminal warrant against Queen for assault with a deadly weapon, and as a condition of his bond, Queen was ordered to have no contact with the mother for one year.Â  The child was born on September 21, 1998.Â  When Queen was notified of the birth in November 1998 he obtained an attorney.Â  He began saving money, prepared a nursery, and arranged for medical insurance for the child.Â  The family court ordered that Queenâ€™s consent to adoption was required under section 20-7-1690 and Abernathy.Â  The supreme court agreed with the family court:

Initially, we find Queen should not be penalized for his actions, or lack thereof, prior to Tannerâ€™s birth.Â  Mother left their apartment when she was approximately 8-10 weeks pregnant, telling Queen she intended to have an abortion.Â  She thereafter lied, telling him she had, in fact, had an abortion in Atlanta.Â  She then made every attempt to conceal from Queen the fact that she had not had an abortion, effectively isolating herself from him and, through court orders, ensuring that Queen could have no contact with her until well after the babyâ€™s birth. 
 As we noted in Abernathy, â€œan unwed fatherâ€™s ability to cultivate his opportunity interest in his child can be thwarted by the refusal of the mother to accept the fatherâ€™s expressions of interest in and commitment to the child. . . . To mandate strict compliance with section 20-7-1690(A)(5)(b) would make an unwed fatherâ€™s right to withhold his consent to adoption dependent upon the whim of the unwed mother.â€Â  313 S.C. at 32-33, 437 S.E.2d at 29.Â  This is clearly such a case.Â  Given Motherâ€™s representations that she had obtained an abortion, coupled with her extraordinary efforts to conceal her pregnancy from Queen, we find the preponderance of the evidence amply demonstrates that Queenâ€™s failure to support during the pregnancy was through no fault of his own and, accordingly, we decline to require literal compliance with the statute.
