The family court found Queen had made sufficient efforts in that he had â€œestablished a nursery, arranged for health insurance and began a savings account for the child.â€Â  We agree.Â  While Queen conceded he had not paid support during the ten-month period prior to the hearing, he testified he was willing to do so, and would reimburse the adoptive parents for their expenses.Â  Further, due to a February 1999 order preventing the disclosure of the identity of the adoptive parents, Queen was unaware of the name or identity of the Does, and/or their location.Â  Under these circumstances, we simply cannot say that Queenâ€™s failure to support or visit Tanner defeats his constitutional interest in establishing a relationship with his son. 
  When approached by the Doeâ€™s attorney, at which time Queen learned of Tannerâ€™s existence, Queen declined to sign a consent to adoption, instead indicating he needed to contact his attorney.Â  For reasons unknown to this Court, his attorney sought and obtained an unlimited extension in which to file responsive pleadings such that an answer to the Doeâ€™s complaint was not filed until the day of the hearing.Â  Although Queen testified he was willing and able to support the child, and had money in savings for Tanner, his mother testified that Queenâ€™s attorney never advised him to send any money to the Does. 
