Queen, 347 S.C. at 8-10, 552 S.E.2d at 763-64 (footnote omitted).
Arscott v. Bacon, 351 S.C. 44, 567 S.E.2d 898 (Ct. App. 2002), is our most recent decision regarding consent for adoption by an unwed father.Â  Edgar Bacon and Mary Ford began a sexual relationship in May 1999.Â  Ford discovered she was pregnant in October 1999.Â  Approximately two weeks later, she told Bacon she had had an abortion.Â  In November, Bacon ended the relationship.Â  Mary Ford was arrested for robbing Baconâ€™s home and was incarcerated.Â  Unconvinced that she had been pregnant or had gone through with an abortion, Bacon inquired at the local jail whether Ford was pregnant, and jail authorities indicated that she claimed to be pregnant.Â  Upon her release, Ford stayed at a womenâ€™s shelter.Â  Bacon drove by the shelter many times in an effort to catch a glimpse of her.Â  Ford delivered the child in May 2000 and gave it up for adoption.Â  On July 17, 2000, Ford appeared in criminal court on the burglary charge and informed Bacon that she had given birth, although Bacon still was not convinced she had ever been pregnant.Â  Finally, Bacon was served with notice of the adoption action in August.Â  He opposed the adoption, claiming Ford had concealed the pregnancy.
After analyzing Abernathy, Queen, Parag, and Black, we concluded Bacon had not satisfied the requirements of the statute and precedent.

 This is not a â€œthwarted birth fatherâ€ case.Â  In his answer, Bacon alleged Ford concealed the pregnancy from him and the first notice he had of the parental relationship was service of the complaint.Â  The facts indicate otherwise.Â  Ford told Bacon in October 1999 that she was pregnant.Â  Although she told him she was going to have an abortion, Bacon stated he did not believe her, and she never produced the written proof which Bacon requested.Â  Bacon asked authorities if Ford was pregnant and was advised she had completed a jail form indicating she was.Â  Bacon continually asked people if Ford appeared pregnant.Â  He drove past a local health care facility to see if he could observe her entering or leaving.Â  He knew Ford was living in the community and staying at a local womenâ€™s shelter.Â  Although she could not contact him due to the conditions of her criminal bond, Bacon was not legally prohibited from contacting her or having someone else contact her.Â  Most importantly, from July 17 to August 16, Bacon did nothing, despite knowing that Ford had a child and he could be the father.
