The instant case is readily distinguishable from Abernathy and Queenâ€”the two cases in which our supreme court has found a fatherâ€™s consent to adoption necessary.Â  Consent cases involve a fact-intensive analysis, and the decisions in both Abernathy and Queen were predicated upon unusual facts.Â  Arscott, 351 S.C. at 48, 567 S.E.2d at 900 (â€œThe importance of analyzing the facts of each specific case cannot be overstated.â€); Abernathy, 313 S.C. at 31, 437 S.E.2d at 29 (â€œ[W]e must ascertain the interaction between the requirements of section 20-7-1690(A)(5)(b) and the unusual facts before us.â€); Queen, 347 S.C. at 10, 552 S.E.2d at 764 (â€œIn our view, under the very limited facts of this case, we find Queen demonstrated sufficient prompt and good faith efforts[.]â€).
