 Queen was a thwarted birth father case.Â  The mother misled the father into believing she had had an abortion and obtained a warrant whereby Queen was ordered to have no contact with her.Â  After learning about the baby, Queen put away money for the child, arranged for the childâ€™s medical insurance, and prepared a nursery.Â  Here, Roe maintained contact with Melanie for only the first half of her pregnancy.Â  It was Roeâ€”not Melanieâ€”who ended the contact.Â  Melanie never refused Roeâ€™s help, but rather requested it, informing him, â€œI canâ€™t do it by myself.â€Â  Further, Melanie attempted to reach Roe on several occasions, but he was apparently avoiding her in a surreptitious attempt to mislead her into believing he was divorcing his wife.Â  His contributions to her were de minimis.Â  In Queen, the court noted that â€œQueenâ€™s failure to support during the pregnancy was through no fault of his own[.]â€Â  In contrast, the blame for Roeâ€™s failure to support Melanie during her pregnancy falls squarely on his shoulders.Â  
