II.Â  Best-Interests Analysis
Roe contends the judge erred by going beyond the scope of the hearing and engaging in a best-interests analysis.Â  The parties stipulated prior to trial that the Does were seeking only adoption and did not have an alternative pleading for custody.Â  Therefore, had Roeâ€™s consent been required, Roe would have been granted custody.Â  Given the stipulation, Roe contends the court should not have addressed the childâ€™s best interests. We disagree.Â  
The family courtâ€™s decision was based on Roeâ€™s failure to comply with the statute and case law, independent of considerations of the childâ€™s best interests.Â  The family courtâ€™s order stated: â€œIt is clear, and this Court holds, that Mr. Roe failed both the literal language of the statute and failed to exercise his responsibilities pursuant to the Common Law Precedent.â€Â  The courtâ€™s legal conclusion stands on its own.Â  Although the best-interests finding was not required, the court did not err in separately considering the childâ€™s best interests.Â  As we stated in Arscott, â€œ[I]n the ultimate analysis, this courtâ€™s lodestar is always the best interests of the child.â€Â  Arscott, 351 S.C. at 55, 567 S.E.2d at 903.Â  Therefore, the courtâ€™s best-interests analysis does not constitute reversible error.Â Â Â Â  
III.Â  Termination of Roeâ€™s Parental Rights
Roe argues that even if section 20-7-1690 and Abernathy did not require his consent to the adoption, his parental rights should not have been terminated.Â  He maintains that because his parental rights should not have been terminated, the notice provision of section 20-7-1374 allows him to â€œfully participate in the adoption proceedings and assert his independent causes of action for custody.â€Â  
A.Â  Preservation
This argument was not raised in Roeâ€™s Rule 59(e) motion, and does not appear to be preserved.Â  An issue cannot be raised for the first time on appeal, but must have been raised to and ruled upon by the trial judge to be preserved for appellate review.Â  Lucas v. Rawl Family Ltd. Pâ€™ship, 359 S.C. 505, 598 S.E.2d 712 (2004); Iâ€™On, L.L.C. v. Town of Mt. Pleasant, 338 S.C. 406, 526 S.E.2d 716 (2000); Austin v. Specialty Transp. Services, Inc., 358 S.C. 298, 594 S.E.2d 867 (Ct. App. 2004); see also Ellie, Inc. v. Miccichi, 358 S.C. 78, 594 S.E.2d 485 (Ct. App. 2004) (noting it is axiomatic than an issue cannot be raised for the first time on appeal).Â  An issue is not preserved where the trial court does not explicitly rule on an argument and the appellant does not make a Rule 59(e) motion to alter or amend the judgment.Â  Hawkins v. Mullins, 359 S.C. 497, 597 S.E.2d 897 (Ct. App. 2004).
Roe filed a Rule 59(e) motion raising several issues, but the motion did not mention the courtâ€™s termination of his parental rights.Â  Moreover, at the Rule 59(e) hearing, Roeâ€™s counsel acknowledged the courtâ€™s termination of his parental rights in passing and did not assert that the termination was in error.Â  In asking the court to grant Roe supervised visitation counsel stated: â€œI know this is getting into a whole new issue here and the court certainly has ruled that his rights are to be terminated under this order.Â  But I would ask the court and in reviewing this to address that issue as to whether or not Mr. Roe should be afforded any visitation.â€Â  (Emphasis added.)Â  Roe never complained to the family court of the termination of his parental rights.Â  Because Roe did not raise this issue in his Rule 59(e) motion, he may not raise it for the first time on appeal.
B.Â  Merits of the TerminationÂ  
Even were this issue preserved, the family court properly denied Roeâ€™s parental rights.Â  The United States Supreme Court case, Lehr v. Robinson, 463 U.S. 248 (1983), elucidated that a biological father has a limited window in which to secure for himself Constitutional protection of the father-child relationship:

