In the case sub judice, the family court extended Roe his procedural and substantive due process rights and determined he had failed to demonstrate the level of commitment to the responsibilities of parenthood that would trigger constitutional protection.Â  Roe correctly asserts that, pursuant to S.C. Code Ann. section 20-7-1770 (Supp. 2005), biological parents lose their rights over the adoptee after a final decree of adoption is entered.Â  However, nothing in the statute prevents this process from being completed in a bifurcated fashion as the court did here.Â  
The family court adjudicated Roeâ€™s claim that his consent was required for adoption.Â  By requesting remand to determine whether adoption by the Does would be in Jayâ€™s best interest, Roe is essentially seeking an impermissible second attempt at preventing the adoption.Â  The family court did not err in terminating Roeâ€™s parental rights.Â  Further, because his rights were properly terminated, Roe is not entitled to notice of the final adoption proceeding pursuant to S.C. Code Ann. section 20-7-1734(A) (Supp. 2005).Â  See id. (â€œNotice of any proceeding initiated pursuant to this Subarticle 7 of Article 11 of Chapter 7 of Title 20 must be given to the persons or agencies specified in subsection (B) of this section, unless the person has given consent or relinquishment or parental rights have been terminated.â€) (emphasis added). 
CONCLUSION
The order of the family court is 
 AFFIRMED.
